core

### Description

Please consider exporting ChangeDetectionScheduler and ChangeDetectionSchedulerImpl.

When providing custom noop zone implementation, we also need to provide ChangeDetectionScheduler.
Angular code does this:
```ts
export function provideZonelessChangeDetection(): EnvironmentProviders {
  return makeEnvironmentProviders([
    {provide: ChangeDetectionScheduler, useExisting: ChangeDetectionSchedulerImpl},
    {provide: NgZone, useClass: NoopNgZone},
  ]);
}
```

I would like to do the same, with my own NgZone implementation.

### Proposed solution

Please make ChangeDetectionScheduler and ChangeDetectionSchedulerImpl part of public API.

### Alternatives considered

I have to do this dirty hack for now:
```ts
export function provideZonelessChangeDetectionX(): EnvironmentProviders {
  const envProviders = (ɵprovideZonelessChangeDetection() as any);
  const providers = envProviders['ɵproviders'];
  providers[1] = { provide: NgZone, useClass: NoopNgZoneX };
  return envProviders;
}
```
I hope it's temporary :)

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

Please consider modifying the default NoopZone implementation.

Right now, if some code uses Zone.onStable() or Zone.onMicrotaskEmpty(), it will not work in a zoneless Angular app.

But if onStable() and onMicrotaskEmpty() implementations will emit in setTimeout(), everything works great.
Here you can find the demo:
https://stackblitz.com/edit/stackblitz-starters-sbyvuz?file=src%2Fmain.ts

In that demo, you can see that with the default noop zone implementation, when you move the pointer over buttons, tooltips are not displayed, and toasts are not displayed when you click a button.

But if you use custom implementation (uncomment line 31 and comment 30), everything works fine.

NG Bootstrap is not the only library that uses Zone.onStable(), I believe there is a lot of code that does, and there is nothing wrong with it (it's not a bug of NG Bootstrap or other libraries and apps).

### Proposed solution

Here is the code that demonstrates the idea:
```ts
import { type EnvironmentProviders, EventEmitter, NgZone, ɵprovideZonelessChangeDetection } from "@angular/core";
import { ReplaySubject } from "rxjs";

class ReplayEmitter<T> extends ReplaySubject<T> {
  emit(v: T) {
    this.next(v);
  }

  constructor(_isAsync?: boolean) {
    super(1);
  }
}

export class NoopNgZoneX implements NgZone {
  readonly hasPendingMicrotasks = false;
  readonly hasPendingMacrotasks = false;
  readonly isStable = true;
  readonly onUnstable = new EventEmitter<any>();

  get onMicrotaskEmpty() {
    const e = new ReplayEmitter<any>();
    setTimeout(() => e.next(null));
    return e as unknown as EventEmitter<any>;
  }

  get onStable() {
    const e = new ReplayEmitter<any>();
    setTimeout(() => e.next(null));
    return e as unknown as EventEmitter<any>;
  }

  readonly onError = new EventEmitter<any>();

  run<T>(fn: (...args: any[]) => T, applyThis?: any, applyArgs?: any): T {
    return fn.apply(applyThis, applyArgs);
  }

  runGuarded<T>(
    fn: (...args: any[]) => any,
    applyThis?: any,
    applyArgs?: any
  ): T {
    return fn.apply(applyThis, applyArgs);
  }

  runOutsideAngular<T>(fn: (...args: any[]) => T): T {
    return fn();
  }

  runTask<T>(
    fn: (...args: any[]) => T,
    applyThis?: any,
    applyArgs?: any,
    _name?: string
  ): T {
    return fn.apply(applyThis, applyArgs);
  }
}
```
I took the code of `NoopNgZone` from the source code of Angular, and modified 2 fields (`onMicrotaskEmpty`, `onStable`), everything else left as is.

### Alternatives considered

I tried to emit synchronously (works only for a few cases), and tried to emit in `Promise.resolve()` (doesn't work well for every case). `setTimeout()` works great for every case.

